Dewey  Thomas Edmund Dewey (Oxford, Nueva York, 26 de marzo de 1902-Manhasset, Nueva York, 16 marzo de 1971) fue un político y abogado estadounidense, que se desempeñó como el 48.º y 49.º gobernador de Nueva York, desde 1943 hasta 1955. También fue el candidato republicano en las elecciones presidenciales de 1944 y 1948.  Nacido en el estado de Nueva York, Dewey se graduó de la Universidad de Nueva York en 1923 y se convirtió en abogado en 1927. En 1938, fue elegido prosecutor (fiscal) del Condado de Nueva York, y en 1942, se convirtió en gobernador de Nueva York después de derrotar al gobernador demócrata, Franklin D. Roosevelt Jr.  Durante su mandato como gobernador, Dewey se enfocó en la reforma administrativa y la reducción de impuestos, y también se esforzó por combatir el crimen y la delincuencia en la ciudad de Nueva York. En 1944, Dewey fue el candidato republicano en las elecciones presidenciales, pero fue derrotado por el presidente demócrata, Franklin D. Roosevelt. En 1948, volvió a ser el candidato republicano, pero una vez más fue derrotado por el presidente Harry S. Truman.  Dewey abandonó la política en 1955 y se convirtió en abogado y consultor en asuntos públicos. También fue profesor de derecho en la Universidad de Nueva York y la Universidad de Columbia. Murió en 1971 a causa de un ataque al corazón.  ## Referencias  1.  «Thomas E. Dewey». National Governors Association. Archivado desde el original el 17 de marzo de 2021. He entered the Imperial Japanese Army Academy in 1911 and was commissioned as a second lieutenant in the infantry. He later attended the Army War College and served in various staff and command positions during the 1930s and early 1940s.  ## World War II  Kuribayashi was given command of the Japanese 35th Army on Iwo Jima in June 1944, shortly before the start of the battle. His mission was to defend the island against the Americans, who were planning to use it as a base for bomber raids on Japan. Kuribayashi was a highly respected and experienced officer, but he was also known for his unconventional approach to warfare. He was a student of the works of Sun Tzu and other ancient Chinese strategists, and he believed that the key to victory was to avoid confrontation whenever possible and to use guerrilla tactics and other unconventional methods to disrupt the enemy's plans.  Kuribayashi's strategy for defending Iwo Jima was to make the island as unappealing a target as possible to the Americans. He ordered his men to construct elaborate tunnels and fortifications throughout the island, and to use their knowledge of the terrain to attack the Americans from unexpected angles. He also ordered his men to use the island's natural features, such as caves and bunkers, to their advantage.  The battle for Iwo Jima was one of the bloodiest and most intense of the war. The Americans landing on 19 February 1945, and after a month of fighting, Kuribayashi's forces were forced to surrender on 23 March. During the battle, Kuribayashi's men inflicted heavy casualties on the Americans, but they were ultimately outnumbered and outgunned.  Kuribayashi was killed on 16 January 1945, when a mortar round struck his headquarters during a nighttime air raid. He was posthumously awarded the Order of the Golden Kite, 3rd Class, for his leadership and bravery during the battle.  ## Legacy  Kuribayashi is remembered as one of the most effective and innovative Japanese commanders of World War II. His unconventional approach to warfare and his focus on guerrilla tactics and hit-and-run attacks were a major factor in the Japanese ability to hold out against the Americans on Iwo Jima for so long. His legacy is celebrated in Japan, where he is remembered as a hero and a model of military leadership.
